<DOC><DOCNO> AP881004-0060 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0619EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Pakistan-Killings     10-04 0315</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Killings,0326</SECOND><HEAD>More Deaths Reported In Riot-Torn Pakistani City</HEAD><BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>HYDERABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police have rounded up about 150people as they investigate bloody ethnic-related shooting spreesthat began Friday in Hyderabad and spread to Karachi, a newspaperreported today.   More than 215 died people died in Hyderabad and Karachi, 100miles to the southwest, during five days of bloody clashes betweenIndian immigrants called Mohajirs and Sindhi separatists seekingindependence for the southern province of Sind.   The official Pakistan Times newspaper said foreigners wereincluded among those arrested. They were not identified.   Meanwhile, the death toll in the violence continued to creep uptoday as police said eight people were killed during a curfew breakthe day before.   There were no immediate reports of renewed shooting when policeallowed people out of their homes for two hours this morning.   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan ordered police roadblocks aroundHyderabad, where more than 160 people died and Karachi, Pakistan'slargest city, where more than 50 died.   Ishaq Khan, after a visit Monday to both cities, said the24-hour roadblocks were being set up to put a lid on furtherviolence as well as search out suspects in the recent killings.   The army, which has been patrolling the cities in armoredpersonnel carriers, will back up police at the roadblocks, he said.   The president also called for a legislative overhaul that wouldlead to greater gun control, according to the official news agency,APP.   Both Hyderabad and Karachi, with eight million people, have beenthe scene of violent ethnic clashes between Indian immigrants andSindhi separatists.   The militant Sindhis are members of the Jeay Sind Movement.   The Mohajirs, who comprise more than 40 percent of theprovincial population, have formed the Mohajir Quami Movement toseek recognition as a fifth nationality in addition to the Sindhis,Punjabis, Baluchis and Pathans.</TEXT></DOC>